  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious offense with significant penalties. The penalties can include:\n\n1. **Imprisonment**: Convictions for money laundering can result in substantial prison sentences. For example:\n   - Under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (laundering of monetary instruments), individuals can face up to 20 years in prison for each count.\n   - Under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from unlawful activity), individuals can face up to 10 years in prison.\n\n2. **Fines**: The fines for money laundering can be substantial, with amounts varying based on the specific statute violated:\n   - Under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956, fines can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n   - Under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957, fines can be up to $250,000 or twice the value of the property involved, whichever is greater.\n\n3. **Forfeiture**: The government can seize and forfeit any property involved in or traceable to the money laundering offense. This can include cash, bank accounts, real estate, and other assets.\n\n4. **Enhanced Penalties**: Certain aggravating factors, such as money laundering involving funds derived from drug trafficking or other serious crimes, can result in enhanced penalties, including longer prison sentences and higher fines.\n\n5. **Conspiracy and Aiding/Abetting**: Individuals who conspire to commit money laundering or aid and abet in the commission of money laundering can face the same penalties as those who directly commit the offense.\n\n6. **Corporate Liability**: Corporations and other entities can also be held liable for money laundering, potentially facing hefty fines and other penalties, including the loss of licenses or the ability to conduct business.\n\nIt's important to note that these penalties can vary based on the specifics of the case, including the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and the defendant's criminal history. Additionally, money laundering charges can often be brought in conjunction with other charges, such as fraud or drug trafficking, which can result in cumulative penalties. \n\nLegal outcomes depend on the facts of each case, so consulting with an attorney for specific advice is crucial if facing such charges.",
